node.text:
There’s a distinctive spirit that inhabits vintage designs. An invaluable patina of living over a span of time and now within a new context of era, of place. I love infusing vintage into all of my environments. Giving historical pieces a new lens adds an incomparable layer of depth, tension and interest into a space. My curatorial process always includes visits to flea markets and vintage shows around the world. The sense of discovery and allure of the hunt for unique, historic treasures is incredibly compelling. 

The Round Top antiques fair @roundtopantiquestexas
in Texas is one of my favorite spots for one-of-a-kind, soulful vintage designs. It is a weeklong, full-sensory exploration of materiality, scale and texture through a profound cross-section of art and design periods. Oftentimes I will buy pieces that speak to me even if they are not the right fit for a certain project I am shopping for at that particular moment, as instinct and serendipity eventually guide the anomalous object to its perfect place. A touch of extraordinary makes design more meaningful. XK

node.text: I come from a long line of working women, who didn’t always have time to show me the ropes when it came to cooking. Instead, I picked up my culinary skills from close friends, like @lenawaldjewelry, an amazing cook who I love to help in the kitchen. She’s taught me so much, and passed on many tips and recipes. I particularly love Lena’s guacamole, and when I made some for another dear friend, Richard Christiansen, he couldn’t get enough of it either. Richard’s @flamingo_estate grows an abundance of produce, so we decided to film a step-by-step guide to Lena’s guac recipe in his kitchen, using items picked straight from the Estate’s garden. The guac tastes even better with such fresh ingredients, and Richard’s kitchen is the perfect place for cooking with friends. I hope you’ll try out the recipe yourself and enjoy the process, and the guac, as much as we did. XK

node.text: SWEET AS HONEY. I always keep my kitchen stocked with delicious honey from @flamingo_estate as I use it as an everyday natural sweetener. I was curious to know how it was made, so I visited my close friend Richard Christiansen whose bees work hard in his garden and orchard — Richard is the owner of the @flamingo_estate and founder of @chandeliercreative and @owlbureau. Putting on the full beekeeper’s suit, interacting with the hive, and harvesting the honey myself was such a fun way to learn all about apiculture. The wild abundance of plants at Flamingo Estate makes the honey so nutritious and flavorful. As well as the honey bees, the lush gardens surrounding this iconic pink Estate – recently renovated by @studioko in Paris – are now planted with over 150 botanical species and offer a home to hummingbirds, owls and butterflies. A true oasis in the city. XK

node.text: I joined my fellow @masterclass alumni and award-winning celebrity mixologist Ryan Chetiyawardana – aka @mrlyan – to combine our respective expertise to craft deliciously decadent cocktails for inspired entertaining at home – whether an intimate bedroom brunch for two, a living room gathering with sunset views or virtual summering on the garden patio with friends on Zoom. Join us in an exclusive how-to-video chat, as London-based @mrlyanstudio joins me at my home in Beverly Hills to share techniques and ultra-curated drink recipes that make staying at home a leveled-up occasion for a toast.  Cheers! XK

node.text:
I gave @elledecorationchina a sneak peak of my studio in Los Angeles earlier this year. 

Rumour has it modernist architect Craig Ellwood completed the office building in the 1960s. I designed the space to take influence from the 1970s and 80s, choosing the snaking @lukelampco and sconces by designer @rosielistudio , and also making some custom. An open plan layout is for easy communication and I usually sit in the middle. 

Big drawers are packed with material palettes so I can get a sense of texture, weight and color for projects. Sketching forms an important part of my creative process. One of my favorite spaces is the conference room decorated with books on photography, fashion and design to provide a library of inspiration. Come back again soon. XK

🎵: In My Room by Frank Ocean

node.text: This summer, my family and I rented a house in Malibu and I partnered with @dominomag to show you the installation. The house was built in the 1940's and was unfurnished. For this room, all the furniture and art were inspired by the original wood paneling. Vintage and contemporary pieces bring this barren space back to life while paying respect to the original design elements of the house. We are going to be showing you all the transformation of this empty space into a stylish seaside home. XK

node.title: HOW TO STYLE A LIVING ROOM

node.text:
The hills are alive with wild flowers!  My foraging journeys continues, this time out of my backyard. I met up with floral designer and collaborator @isaisafloral in the canyons of Malibu near her home this week. We collected bunches of wild mustard, wild castor and echium. The gorgeous bright yellow flowers of the mustard plants are edible and make bountiful bouquets of sunshine for back home. They are also inherently invasive to the hillside and ideal for cutting, especially from the roots, allowing space for native plants to grow. When the wild mustard is left untouched it dries out over the summer and becomes fire fuel. I’ve learned so much from Sophia on these hikes. It’s so important to be connected to the natural world for a greater sense of well-being. XK 
Song: You &  Me - Flume

node.text:
Flora Fantasy. Collaborating with other artists is about discovery and bringing a singular synergistic perspective to the design landscape. I have always loved partnering with inspiring talents in different creative fields. You gain so much knowledge from others and their expertise -- it’s an education in new and different materiality, processes and disciplines.  We’re all keeping this spirit of inspiration, fun and friendship alive in new and creative ways now, and I’m excited to share the alchemy that I’ve been creating behind the screens with some of my favorite artists.  @isaisafloral guided me into my yard to harvest blooming wisteria and philodendron leaves and create some floral magic back inside….the result was breathtaking.  Thank you, Sophia, for the virtual foraging workshop! XK

node.text: GO WITH THE FLOW. Corners are naturally carved out spaces that lend special moments for expression. Artful silhouettes, whether sculpture, furniture, lighting or other considered curations, are treated to their own spotlight, yet together create a dialogue that distinctly varies from each unique point of perspective. Where my foyer meets the entry to the den there’s a communicative composition between a favorite marble sculpture, an artful sconce, and a chair made from Paraffin and carnauga wax, and carbon fibers by Ida Elke. A meeting of meaningful designs. XK

node.text: RSVP. Entertaining is all about the experience, the emotional response. Creating curated moments around all the senses sets an inherently festive mood and brings a space wonderfully to life. A thoughtful mix of textiles, metals, marble, objets d’art, lighting and florals create diverse points of interest, of conversation and full sensory engagement. It’s an open invitation for guests to enjoy time together and leave with lasting memories. Shana tovah! Happy new year! XK

node.text: OUTSIDE IN. Exterior architecture and natural surroundings are important considerations when designing an interior environment. Windows are like framed pieces of art that invite the outdoors in, bringing an array of visual elements — geometries, patterns and oftentimes changing colors — into a space. Infusing various vantage points of the exterior into a design creates an engaging and expansive setting that is super authentic to its location. XK

node.text: LIFE IS JUST BETTER IN MARBLE. Marble is the ultimate muse. Its captivating visual texture, cooling touch and remarkable organic patterning make it so damn sexy. I am drawn to this venerated earth element time and time again in my work. Rock on. XK

node.text: COLOR CRUSH. The interiors of @austinproperhotel are infused with a pigment-charged color story indigenous to the city of Austin, featuring a juxtaposition of copper hues, deep blues and tanned leathers. Vintage chairs are given fresh new spirit in reupholstered designs upon vintage carpets, selectively sourced over five years that ground each intimate seating area. XK

node.text: TIMBER. From grain to tone to finish – like a beautifully black charred wood – there is such variance in wood that provides an endless assortment of options for design. On a recent visit to Austin, I toured the factory of @deltamillworks (the ultimate candy store of lumber sources) to scope out material for an upcoming project. I love to experience in person before finalizing my selection. Often the smallest details make the biggest impact. XK

node.text:
LOST & FOUND. I have always felt a deep connection to vintage furniture designs. They resonate with history and embody a definitive period of time, of craftsmanship, of love for the art of living not just existing. Infusing a space with vintage pieces creates a highly personalized, soulful and sensory experience — a belonging to the bigger design journey. 

In our living room by the sea, the iconic, curvaceous Tobia Scarpa sofa and chaise lounge from the 1970s composes an oasis of time, mood and space with Diggama, a lounge chair with adjustable brass feet designed in 1957 by Ignazio Gardella and the super textural steel and jute rope lounge chair by Dan Johnson circa 1950. XK
